<subSubSection id="1DD3340E7F4C4721F2FFA909BCF72F37" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="17D8E7AF90597187EB00AAE300F5744A" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="20B72699AEF16625217399B973BAC80F" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis id="41F7BB31E6BD64A6167FA67ABAE853C0" bold="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
(
<figureCitation id="CE6C2D885496726FA3D0DB804E712DE0" captionStart="Figure 15" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figure 15. Distribution of Lepidium aegrum, Lepidium amissum, Lepidium castellanum (Kermadec Islands only), Lepidium banksii, and Lepidium crassum." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10753" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
. Endemic. New Zealand, South Island, Marlborough Sounds (Queen Charlotte, Kenepuru and Pelorus Sounds), Nelson (Waimea Estuary, Totaranui, Separation Point, Wainui Inlet), north-west Nelson (Karamea).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="965C83D97C661BC903F3303310A36AB7" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="recognition">
<paragraph id="1E804B0EF5A318BCA7396A62FC574D0B" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Recognition.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E7347196CBEF720D4462725C5CD75F20" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<taxonomicName id="494D92EB881A150962EB311C9858A79E" authorityName="Kirk, Stud. Fl. N. Z, 35" authorityYear="1899" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="banksii">
<emphasis id="8526BE1E5F9C33E54BA4B1D6155C8127" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Lepidium banksii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is recognised by the clavate hairs on the pedicels (
<figureCitation id="7A103DE33885BAB3DA55693050D6195B" captionStart="Figure 24" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figure 24. (A) Pedicel of Lepidium banksii showing hairs, (B) emasculated flowers showing nectaries, ovary and stigma. Scale bars = 1 mm" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10762" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 24A</figureCitation>
), mostly filiform petals, styles that spread at the apex into a broad plate (
<figureCitation id="ABCD4C9DECEA6A6D18452CB86AA47A3E" captionStart="Figure 24" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figure 24. (A) Pedicel of Lepidium banksii showing hairs, (B) emasculated flowers showing nectaries, ovary and stigma. Scale bars = 1 mm" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10762" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 24B</figureCitation>
), and silicles that have a prominent apical notch (
<figureCitation id="9B403AE4B4EC0C85D49F9CFE1821D4BD" captionStart="Figure 25" captionStartId="F25" captionText="Figure 25. Mature silicle of Lepidium banksii. CHR 509034. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10763" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
). In comparison, the styles of the other 
<taxonomicName id="74E9FAE12498F9D373EA0A59361E83D1" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="08675998C6E15AF59AFDDB48AED221CB" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Lepidium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species except for 
<taxonomicName id="374AA46646DB257A73FB312BA4943C14" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seditiosum">
<emphasis id="551FC804015CFFB2C5823EE34DDF86B1" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Lepidium seditiosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, are cylindrical for their whole length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A088A88CCD1A6EA30AEFDD3F8F69F873" lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="E3968F0E97889BE1407FC267B876CA9E" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="018764E4AFE323A373941DC441C484B6" lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<taxonomicName id="43A4F2720E56C2AE1A5193155A7568E6" authorityName="Kirk, Stud. Fl. N. Z, 35" authorityYear="1899" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="banksii">
<emphasis id="B8D86D7A058BBCF5DEDE4F392E1352D7" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Lepidium banksii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a strictly coastal species favouring rubble slopes, boulder beaches, exposed rocky headlands (
<figureCitation id="E9E025FEC42AD5F22D4D5E23D6204646" captionStart="Figure 22" captionStartId="F22" captionText="Figure 22. Young wild plant of Lepidium banksii (image: S. Walls)." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10760" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
), and sparsely vegetated cliff faces 
<pageBreakToken id="78D1563C00D53075E3A5F507F01A6B65" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" start="start">usually</pageBreakToken>
near penguin colonies or low lying, estuarine shell banks and sand and shell barrier islands used as high tide roosts by wading birds.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E5336F0227E70806502B4B16E4AD2266" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="conservation status">
<paragraph id="D9BD2EFE849C3E4C678DD014AEAA2954" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Conservation Status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B7FC8417C00358C66696977A22FDA1A1" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicName id="550888BC1DAB0975DF538F2C85414C4E" authorityName="Kirk, Stud. Fl. N. Z, 35" authorityYear="1899" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="banksii">
<emphasis id="9DAB3A7959F9666747202F3D271DA5EE" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Lepidium banksii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is currently listed as 'Threatened/Nationally Critical CD, 
<normalizedToken id="17AE54E876956FE3ED38C38C3BE3CB5B" originalValue="EF’">EF'</normalizedToken>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="B2CB0AF820A9556D66F6C5639B7EA87C" author="de Lange, PJ" journalOrPublisher="Annals of Botany" pageId="113" pageNumber="114" publicationUrl="10.1080/00288250909509794" refId="B26" refString="de Lange, PJ, Norton, DA, Courtney, SP, Heenan, PB, Barkla, JW, Cameron, EK, Hitchmough, R, Townsend, AJ, 2009. Threatened and uncommon plants New Zealand Journal of Botany 47: 61-96. ., 10.1080/00288250909509794" title="Threatened and uncommon plants New Zealand Journal of Botany 47: 61 - 96." url="10.1080/00288250909509794" year="2009">de Lange et al. (2009)</bibRefCitation>
. Both 
<bibRefCitation id="C8BE6DDEF9C6922206F0676FE53396D0" author="de Lange, PJ" journalOrPublisher="New Zealand Geographic" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" pagination="14 - 15" refId="B16" refString="de Lange, PJ, 2006. Unsung heroes. New Zealand Geographic 81: 14 - 15" title="Unsung heroes." volume="81" year="2006">de Lange (2006)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="8018620383533E5DC7485B102858B5D3" author="Courtney, S" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B14" refString="Courtney, S, 2009. A plant on the edge - the trials of coastal peppercress recovery. Celebrating our native plant life. Conference Proceedings 8-10 August 2008. New Zealand Plant Conservation Network. Wellington. http://nzpcn.org.nz/publications/NZPCN%20Conference%20Proceedings%202008_web%20version.pdf." title="A plant on the edge - the trials of coastal peppercress recovery. Celebrating our native plant life. Conference Proceedings 8 - 10 August 2008. New Zealand Plant Conservation Network. Wellington. http: // nzpcn. org. nz / publications / NZPCN % 20 Conference % 20 Proceedings % 202008 _ web % 20 version. pdf" year="2009">Courtney (2009)</bibRefCitation>
describe the conservation management of this species, noting that there are probably no naturally occurring plants of 
<taxonomicName id="19B8E549833235CEF2DF85B66C8CB270" authorityName="Kirk, Stud. Fl. N. Z, 35" authorityYear="1899" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="banksii">
<emphasis id="A3206F06AA64DD9BA82B3CCEE2A0F9C3" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Lepidium banksii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
left in the wild, with all those known the result of deliberate plantings and sowing of seed. As such, the qualifier 
<normalizedToken id="E1C998CD43C83CC4680F939180194928" originalValue="‘EW’">'EW'</normalizedToken>
(Extinct in Wild) should be added to the current threat listing. The most recent census of the numbers of 
<taxonomicName id="90E122C134DC11783DC3ED65108B7A21" authorityName="Kirk, Stud. Fl. N. Z, 35" authorityYear="1899" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="banksii">
<emphasis id="20CE7C4118D7A32DD7A094FD2AC9B13B" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Lepidium banksii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
present in the 
<normalizedToken id="0AD7868AAF77D74BFC478F346D0C3485" originalValue="‘wild’">'wild'</normalizedToken>
records 113 plants (
<bibRefCitation id="DC0D25B0A96EFB4143B8499EA7B2101D" author="Courtney, S" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B14" refString="Courtney, S, 2009. A plant on the edge - the trials of coastal peppercress recovery. Celebrating our native plant life. Conference Proceedings 8-10 August 2008. New Zealand Plant Conservation Network. Wellington. http://nzpcn.org.nz/publications/NZPCN%20Conference%20Proceedings%202008_web%20version.pdf." title="A plant on the edge - the trials of coastal peppercress recovery. Celebrating our native plant life. Conference Proceedings 8 - 10 August 2008. New Zealand Plant Conservation Network. Wellington. http: // nzpcn. org. nz / publications / NZPCN % 20 Conference % 20 Proceedings % 202008 _ web % 20 version. pdf" year="2009">Courtney 2009</bibRefCitation>
). Survival of this species is now completely dependent on direct hands-on management (
<bibRefCitation id="484818FD7F2A891B4CAAA5F1CDF2FA48" author="de Lange, PJ" journalOrPublisher="New Zealand Geographic" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" pagination="14 - 15" refId="B16" refString="de Lange, PJ, 2006. Unsung heroes. New Zealand Geographic 81: 14 - 15" title="Unsung heroes." volume="81" year="2006">de Lange 2006</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="0ED5DDDFC5CF8BC6A1E20107584D9486" author="Courtney, S" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" refId="B14" refString="Courtney, S, 2009. A plant on the edge - the trials of coastal peppercress recovery. Celebrating our native plant life. Conference Proceedings 8-10 August 2008. New Zealand Plant Conservation Network. Wellington. http://nzpcn.org.nz/publications/NZPCN%20Conference%20Proceedings%202008_web%20version.pdf." title="A plant on the edge - the trials of coastal peppercress recovery. Celebrating our native plant life. Conference Proceedings 8 - 10 August 2008. New Zealand Plant Conservation Network. Wellington. http: // nzpcn. org. nz / publications / NZPCN % 20 Conference % 20 Proceedings % 202008 _ web % 20 version. pdf" year="2009">Courtney 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
